##Wuhan "closed city" first day record: less hospital beds, protection lack of resources, patient isolation

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

Whether it's a doctor, a nurse, a patient, a suspected patient, a couple going out of town in the middle of the night, a worried mother, or an entrepreneur working overtime, no one mentioned that it's Spring Festival and New Year's Eve

By Fang Gongyi, Liu Chenjing, caijing reporter
Editor | Song Wei

The first 8 hours: The "closure" came suddenly

Some people in Wuhan wake up late, they may be more than the National Internet users know Wuhan "closed city" News.
At around 8:51 a.m. on January 23, they received a text message from China Mobile: the Headquarters of the prevention and control of the new coronavirus-infected pneumonia in Wuhan said that since 10:00 a.m. on January 23,2020, the city bus, subway, ferry, long-distance passenger stations suspended operations. Airports and railway stations are temporarily closed from the Han corridor.
Some people in Wuhan Sleep late, they saw in January 23 at 2 o'clock in the morning Wuhan will be "closed" news, so ready to leave the city overnight.
Wuhan resident Wang Shen woke up at 4 am to see the news, quickly woke up beside his girlfriend, two people booked a January 238:55 am train tickets to Quanzhou, Fujian.
Wang Shen had just canceled the reunion dinner the night before, giving the whole company a holiday in advance. His The Wrong Mans gave his staff time to go home before the sudden "closure" notice, and now he is ready to send his girlfriend out of Wuhan.
Wang Shen told Caijing that the cross-provincial case had a big impact on him: The media reported that a case was confirmed in Dalian because it could not be treated in Wuhan, and he finally chose to fly to Dalian and was diagnosed. So Wang and his girlfriend chose to go out of town alone and stay alone. Although they did not have any symptoms of pneumonia, they decided to spread the risk and go to other cities so that they could see a doctor in time. Perhaps that was the more feasible way out.
They are the epitome of the rush out of Wuhan. At 5:30 a.m. on Jan. 23, some people heading out of town arrived at the convenience store, which was already packed. The clerk told them that this was the third wave of citizens to stock up.
Nearly 10 people were already waiting in line at the entrance of the subway station shortly before 6 o'clock. At 7:15, Wang Shen sent his girlfriend to Wuhan Station. There was a People Mountain People Sea, and he saw that most of them were wearing masks. Trains from Wuhan to Quanzhou Depart as scheduled. But his girlfriend didn't have any temperature checks before she got in the car.
A woman visiting her family in Wuhan from Los Angeles told Caijing that her family panicked when she saw the news. Her daughter was on a flight that afternoon, en route from Wuhan to Xiamen to Los Angeles. She tried her luck at the airport, but when she arrived, she saw a large number of police arriving by bus. The plane could no longer fly. With her daughter's college year just around the corner, she has no choice but to travel first to Macheng, near Wuhan, and then take the high-speed train from Macheng to other places by plane.
She was advised to drive herself to the expressway, but by 3 p.m. on Jan. 23, highways around Wuhan were also closed.
After seeing off his girlfriend on the train, Wang Shen returned to the city, around 9 o'clock he arrived at Wuhan Zhongbai Supermarket to stock up on goods. Many people barely look at the goods, do not choose goods, directly into the fruit and vegetables in the basket. The supermarket has three weighing points, six cash registers, each line of 20 people. On the shelves, 84 disinfectant, restocked the night before, has been sold out.
It is reported that on January 23, most of the supermarket prices in Wuhan in the normal state, that is, the Spring Festival prices in Wuhan in previous years, higher than normal prices by 30%-50% . Luo Xin, a Wuhan resident, bought two bundles of Vegetable Moss, two catties and half green beans, four lotus roots and 113 yuan.
Zhou Xue, who lives in Wuchang, south-east Wuhan, had just got up. He presented with low-grade fever, general weakness, Anorexia and other viral pneumonia symptoms from January 22, and went to six hospitals, until January 23, Wuhan "Fengcheng" news came, has not been the opportunity to see a doctor.
He went to the hospital, either do not receive treatment, or the queue, booking was canceled, many hospitals need to queue all night.
Only two hospitals can be scheduled for outpatient service, one is the central war zone general hospital, but only screening, not treatment, one is the provincial women's health care hospital, but only for pregnant women.
The exhausted Zhou Xue can only take the symptom to go home. He found that her grandmother also began to have a low-grade fever, but she could not turn like a young person to six hospitals for medical treatment, only at home self-isolation, waiting for the latest hospital treatment.
After receiving the news of "closing the city, " Zhou Xue got up and did two things, grabbing food from the supermarket and going to the gas station. In his view, these resources after the "closure" than medical resources are not sufficient, the supermarket has been snapped up vegetables, can only wait for the next day replenishment, and waiting for gas cars lined up a street. Luo Xin, who also came to the gas station, waited 30 minutes without filling up his tank to see if he still had half a tank of gas before driving away.

There's a line at the gas station down the block
Compared with more than suspected patients interviewed by Caijing, Zhou Xue, who owns a car, may be lucky. After the bus, subway, transport modes stop, countless patients, go to the hospital transport options are not many.
The city's taxi-hailing capacity has been sharply reduced because of the epidemic. According to a taxi-hailing platform provided to "CAIJING" reporter data, from January 21, Wuhan orders only to about half of daily orders, January 23, "closed city" orders even fewer. This means that most patients without a car, who can not get a taxi, have to walk to the nearest hospital. Some people want to call an ambulance, but according to the hospital, each hospital has not many ambulances in full attendance, basic can not call.

Second 8 hours: A hospital bed is hard to find

However, even if you go to the hospital, you may not be able to see a doctor.
CAIJING reporter called all the designated hospitals in Wuhan, including the first batch of three hospitals: the City Hankou Hospital, the City Red Cross Hospital and the city seven hospital, and the second batch of four hospitals: the Western district of the city's four hospitals, the city's nine hospitals, the city's Wuchang Hospital, the city's five hospitals, only the Red Cross hospital still has beds, and the other designated hospitals, each with several hundred beds, are already full, and they are sorting through the aisle positions, to prepare a new bed by transferring a common patient, etc. .
In other words, at least 2,000 beds in these hospitals are already full of patients with fever.
Wuhan Xiehe, Tongji these two well-known general hospitals, fever hospital beds are full, can only accept outpatient service. For Zhou Xue such suspected patients, he can only keep calling the hospital to ask about the latest bed situation. Even if it's confirmed or highly doubtful, it's time to take the drug, go home and Quarantine yourself for 3 to 5 days.
He, too, is waiting to hear from his doctor. The European epidemic prevention regulations require doctors to visit patients in case of an epidemic. But as of press time, "CAIJING" has not yet learned that Wuhan Hospital received the relevant deployment, also did not see the community to provide relevant help.
Wuhan's health system has been stretched to the limit in recent days in the face of the epidemic. According to "CAIJING" reporters understand that the designated hospital city seven hospitals can only accept outpatient services, beds are still moving. On the night of January 22nd more than 600 people were admitted, either with mild or severe illness, to be treated with oral medication or fluids. The hospital will be deployed in south-central hospital medical staff support, in a few days to complete the conversion of aisle beds, plans to open 305 beds. At the same time, the hospital also reported the need for scarce resources.
Li Lan, who went from Wuhan to the Taihe Hospital in Shiyan, Hubei Province, was told to go home and wait for the results. There are only 2-3 beds left in the hospital, which can only be provided for the critically ill.
Li Ran back to her hometown before the city was "sealed off" in Wuhan. Prior to her internship in the Department of gastroenterology at Wuhan Tongji Hospital, until she left Tongji Hospital on January 19, it was rare for a gastroenterologist to wear protective clothing, what they saw was an official notification that there was no clear evidence of human-to-human transmission.
The Ophthalmology Department of Wuhan People's Hospital has recently been requisitioned as an infection ward for doctors suspected or confirmed to be infected. They were transferred to a designated hospital at noon on 23 January.
CAIJING reporter learned by telephone that the third and seventh hospitals in Wuhan have been notified by their superiors to become designated hospitals in the past two days and are transferring common patients and arranging beds.
Over the past few days, the number of confirmed and suspected cases in Wuhan has surged to several hundred, and the city's protection level has been upgraded. In particular, after learning that many cases do not have obvious features such as fever, many Wuhan residents'mentality seems to have experienced a roller coaster, from the common mentality of dealing with the flu, to everyone's self-fear. Coupled with the case from Wuhan to Dalian, "closed city" stimulus, there are similar symptoms of the public want to go to the hospital as soon as possible to get treatment, Wuhan Limited medical resources therefore in short supply.
Medical supplies are also in short supply. The Third Hospital, which was told to be designated, did not store enough protective equipment. When contacted by phone at 2 p.m. , doctors had only a handful of masks, caps, and no protective clothing or goggles. The hospital is seeking material support through social channels.
But the third hospital did not have enough protective equipment in reserve. When Caijing contacted the hospital by phone at 2 p.m. on January 23, doctors had only a small number of masks and caps, and no protective clothing or goggles, the hospital is seeking material support through social channels.
Staff at the Wuhan University of Science and Technology told Caijing that doctors currently have only surgical masks to use, no protective clothing, and N95 masks in fever clinics and quarantine areas, and are waiting for material support.
Medical staff at a Hanchuan hospital in Xiaogan, Hubei Province, said some of the N95 masks they had been given had been out of date for nearly a year and could only be effectively sterilized during their shelf life. Some nurses reacted angrily in the work group, the feedback is: do not open, private things to talk about.
According to "CAIJING" reporters understand that Yuantong has opened express transfer, after disinfection can be sent to Wuhan. People from all walks of life are responding to the hospital's request for donations. Wuhan has donated enterprises 2:10 told the "CAIJING" reporter, can go to the foundation or individual donations.
An industry source told reporters that in general, applications for donations are made through the foundation, especially medical consumables and other materials that need to go through professional quality testing, it is rare that designated hospitals and general hospitals are now seeking outside material help. He questioned whether there was any miscommunication or inaction in the middle.
However, a person from a European institution told Caijing that it is still necessary to go through the necessary procedures for overseas donations to enter Wuhan. It is not clear when the tens of thousands of masks they have purchased will be delivered to Wuhan.
In addition to inadequate supplies, some hospitals have limited isolation beds. It is understood that in a hospital in Xiaogan, Hanchuan, Hubei, some suspected patients were transferred to the emergency department after there were not enough beds in the infection department. With suspected patients, trauma patients arriving in the E.R. late at night, and, uh, children who haven't been discharged.
From Jan. 20 to 23, the hospital's emergency department took over more than 160 patients with fever symptoms, a health care worker said. The hospital has imposed partial quarantine since the morning of January 23. The overnight quarantine zone was filled with patients in one day. Other suspected patients were told to "wear a mask and do not move around. ".

The third 8 hours: There's always good news

At 4 p.m. on Jan. 23, the Wuhan Union Hospital released a preliminary diagnosis and treatment plan for upper respiratory tract infection and viral pneumonia, which provides strategies for diagnosis and treatment based on 12 different clinical characteristics. For confirmed cases and suspected cases of home isolation, the drugs most in need are oral Moxifloxacin, Levofloxacin, Oseltamivir and others.
Zhou Xue emotional told the "CAIJING" reporter: "FINALLY OUT OF THE PLAN! " For his such suspected patients, the most afraid is no medical check, no medicine to eat. In the face of a large number of suspected cases, in the absence of a bed confirmed cases, drug programmes and mild cases of cure, at least to reassure people.
But the current stock of drugs is not optimistic. "CAIJING" reporters through the phone to understand the Wuhan several big pharmacies stock situation, the general situation is: The above medicine sold quickly, stock less, the need for temporary purchase. MOXIFLOXACIN is out of stock, down to 20 boxes of Oseltamivir, because of a recent epidemic at the Hankou Railway Station and a pharmacy with heavy foot traffic. And Mask, disinfectant and other materials, as early as in recent days was snapped up.
The Spring Festival and the closure of the city have accelerated the shortage of medicines: All five pharmacies interviewed by Caijing will be closed during the Spring Festival holiday on January 24. Some pharmacies said that the fourth day of the first lunar month (January 28) may be open, depending on the "closed" after the purchase results.

A pharmacy with closed doors after the holidays
At 6 pm on January 23, a light rain began to fall in Wuhan. There were only a few vehicles on the street, and no pedestrians could be seen. Zhou Xue went downstairs to buy medicine and found that the pharmacy had closed. But at the same time, his house downstairs chess room is still lively. This is a popular pastime for Wuhan people, especially during the Spring Festival. Looking in through the window, air conditioning was on, people in thin sweaters were pushing cards, almost no one wearing masks.

Community downstairs in full swing of the chess room
Zhou Xue told the reporter that there are many old people living alone in his neighborhood. Their children work outside, because of the epidemic gave up home for the New Year, but do not trust the family elderly, the community did not provide related condolences, can only go around to find him, hope to help take care of. But Zhou Xue is now a suspected case, he can do, no more than the elderly children outside.
"These old people don't watch the latest news from their mobile phones. They turn on the TV and watch the festive scenes of the new year. They don't know how they will spend the year and how they should go to the hospital if they really feel sick, " Zhou said.
After learning that his girlfriend had arrived safely in Quanzhou, Wang Shen went home and cooked a meal. He had enough food to last a week. After dinner, he went to the office to pick up some things. At this time, Wuhan Guanggu Wisdom Park, the road is very few, but office buildings still have 5,6 lights. Some have gone home, some are working late.

Where people are still working overtime
For most doctors in Wuhan, there is little time for rest. Doctors at Wuhan's No. 5 Hospital were not allowed to leave at night, and other doctors at non-designated hospitals were told on Jan. 23 to cancel their Spring Festival leave and stand by.
After work, doctors in the hospital have shuttle bus, but the station can not pass all doctors near home. "The only way to get to work in the morning is to rely on Didi, " a doctor told CAIJING. But news came in the early hours of January 24 that Didi would suspend its online ride-hailing service in Wuhan at the request of the Wuhan Xinguan pneumonia prevention and control headquarters, for a unified deployment.
On the evening of January 23, when Caijing contacted the city's seventh hospital again, the other party said it was no longer available for interviews and that any information needed would have to be directed to the hospital's media department. At the same time, a designated hospital, which has released information seeking donations, has also received a notice to delete relevant information as soon as possible, and can no longer freely forward similar information.
At around 12 p.m. on January 23, Li Lan came out of Taihe Hospital in Shiyan. She had developed fever and general weakness and was going home to quarantine herself, awaiting the results of a blood draw at the hospital. She told Caijing that she was glad to have returned to her hometown before the city was "closed" because she had been on duty at the hospital, and she thought the city around Wuhan was less crowded and less nervous about seeing a doctor than Wuhan.
Also on the evening of January 23, the Changjiang daily published an article by the deputy head of the Expert Group on self-cure of new coronary pneumonia at home. Seeing this, Zhou decided to give up the plan of getting up early the next day and go to the hospital. He chose to take oral medicine at home in isolation to avoid cross-infection with severe patients in crowded outpatient clinics. At the same time, he reduced the burden of medical resources.
In interviews over the past 24 hours, no one -- doctors, nurses, patients, suspected patients, citizens out of town in the middle of the night, worried mothers, entrepreneurs working overtime -- mentioned that it was Chinese New Year and New Year's Eve.
CAIJING reporter will continue to track the progress of major epidemic prevention and control in Wuhan, and continue to send relevant reports.
(in the article, Wang Shen, Xiao Xue, Luo Xin and Li Lan are assumed names)

Some have gone home, some are working late.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Where people are still working overtime

For most doctors in Wuhan, there is little time for rest. Doctors at Wuhan's No. 5 Hospital were not allowed to leave at night, and other doctors at non-designated hospitals were told on Jan. 23 to cancel their Spring Festival leave and stand by.

After work, doctors in the hospital have shuttle bus, but the station can not pass all doctors near home. "The only way to get to work in the morning is to rely on Didi, " a doctor told CAIJING. But news came in the early hours of January 24 that Didi would suspend its online ride-hailing service in Wuhan at the request of the Wuhan Xinguan pneumonia prevention and control headquarters, for a unified deployment.

On the evening of January 23, when Caijing contacted the city's seventh hospital again, the other party said it was no longer available for interviews and that any information needed would have to be directed to the hospital's media department. At the same time, a designated hospital, which has released information seeking donations, has also received a notice to delete relevant information as soon as possible, and can no longer freely forward similar information.

At around 12 p.m. on January 23, Li Lan came out of Taihe Hospital in Shiyan. She had developed fever and general weakness and was going home to quarantine herself, awaiting the results of a blood draw at the hospital. She told Caijing that she was glad to have returned to her hometown before the city was "closed" because she had been on duty at the hospital, and she thought the city around Wuhan was less crowded and less nervous about seeing a doctor than Wuhan.

Also on the evening of January 23, the Changjiang daily published an article by the deputy head of the Expert Group on self-cure of new coronary pneumonia at home. Seeing this, Zhou decided to give up the plan of getting up early the next day and go to the hospital. He chose to take oral medicine at home in isolation to avoid cross-infection with severe patients in crowded outpatient clinics. At the same time, he reduced the burden of medical resources.

In interviews over the past 24 hours, no one -- doctors, nurses, patients, suspected patients, citizens out of town in the middle of the night, worried mothers, entrepreneurs working overtime -- mentioned that it was Chinese New Year and New Year's Eve.

CAIJING reporter will continue to track the progress of major epidemic prevention and control in Wuhan, and continue to send relevant reports.

(in the article, Wang Shen, Xiao Xue, Luo Xin and Li Lan are assumed names)
